Q: Vigenere Cipher in C: Incomplete Encryption A: <p>In checking out old issues still open during the holiday season, I came across this program example and noted issue.  Even though this issue is quite old, I thought it would be fun and educational to work on.  Testing out the updated code above, it does appear that the changes noted in the good comments were implemented and one does get the proper encrypted output, even when referencing the Wikipedia dissertation for Vigenere encryption and testing out its example.</p>
<p>However, in reviewing the code, there seems to be aspects to the coding that do not follow &quot;usual and customary&quot; coding practices, so even though there may not be a need for a simpler answer to this issue, I thought I would take the opportunity to refactor the code to reduce unnecessary variables and testing as well as expand the functionality to both encrypt and decrypt a message.  Following is a refactored version of this program.</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdbool.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;
#include &lt;ctype.h&gt;

#define ALPHA 26                /* Define constant values to mitigate usage of magic numbers    */
#define SIZE 100

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    /* Define variables to be used up front in lieu of repeatedly defining them within loops    */

    char word[ALPHA], message[SIZE];
    int j = 0, ciphercode;
    long word_length;
    bool valid = true;

    if (argc != 3)
    {
        printf(&quot;Please enter valid command line arguments! \n&quot;);
        printf(&quot;Example: Vignere e abcdefg \n&quot;);
        return 1;
    }

    strcpy(word, argv[2]);

    word_length = strlen(word);                         /* Derive length once as noted in the comments                                  */

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; word_length; i++)
    {
        valid = isalpha(word[i]);

        if (!valid)                                     /* Exit if a non-alphabetic character is found                                  */
            break;

        word[i] = tolower(word[i] - 'a');               /* Derive and store the character offset values - e.g. 'a' has a value of zero  */
    }

    if (valid == false)
    {
        printf(&quot;Please enter only alphabetical characters! \n&quot;);
        return 2;
    }

    printf(&quot;Message..: &quot;);

    if (fgets(message, sizeof(message), stdin) == 0)        /* Using standard input function - do not have CS50 installed               */
        return 2;

    if (strcmp(argv[1], &quot;e&quot;) == 0 || strcmp(argv[1], &quot;E&quot;) == 0)
    {
        printf(&quot;Encrypted: &quot;);

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; strlen(message); i++)           /* Usual and customary way to define and use a &quot;for&quot; loop                   */
        {
            ciphercode = message[i];                        /* Store ASCII value initially in the ciphercode work variable              */

            if (isalpha(ciphercode))                        /* Encrypt if the variable value equates to an alphabetical character       */
            {
                ciphercode = (ciphercode + word[j]);
                j = (j+1) % word_length;
            }

            if ((isupper(message[i]) &amp;&amp; ciphercode &gt; 'Z') || (islower(message[i]) &amp;&amp; ciphercode &gt; 'z'))
                ciphercode -= ALPHA;                        /* Adjust value if ASCII value goes beyond 'Z' or 'z'                       */

            printf(&quot;%c&quot;, ciphercode);
        }

    }
    else
    {
        printf(&quot;Decrypted: &quot;);

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; strlen(message); i++)           /* Usual and customary way to define and use a &quot;for&quot; loop                   */
        {
            ciphercode = message[i];                        /* Store ASCII value initially in the ciphercode work variable              */

            if (isalpha(ciphercode))                        /* Encrypt if the variable value equates to an alphabetical character       */
            {
                ciphercode = (ciphercode - word[j]);
                j = (j+1) % word_length;
            }

            if ((isupper(message[i]) &amp;&amp; ciphercode &lt; 'A') || (islower(message[i]) &amp;&amp; ciphercode &lt; 'a'))
                ciphercode += ALPHA;                        /* Adjust value if ASCII value goes below 'A' or 'a'                        */

            printf(&quot;%c&quot;, ciphercode);
        }

    }

    return 0;

}
</code></pre>
<p>First off, I have no issue with the Harvard &quot;CS50&quot; library and its functions.  I just never have installed it on my virtual machine.  So whenever I have analyzed code that incorporates their functions and variable definitions (e.g. &quot;string&quot;, getString(), and so forth), I just replace that code with functionally equivalent variables or functions found in &quot;stdlib.h&quot; and/or &quot;stdio.h&quot; (e.g. &quot;char *&quot;, &quot;fgets()&quot;, and so forth).</p>
<p>The next thing to note is the replacement of hard-coded numeric values, sometimes referred to as &quot;magic numbers&quot; with defined constants, again to simplify the code.  And to simplify testing so as to not have to determine if the incoming argument character values are uppercase or lowercase, a simple calculation of each character in the argument converts each character to its corresponding offset value.  Doing that simplifies the testing downstream in the code.</p>
<p>Also, in lieu of defining variables that will be used throughout the program within loops, those variables are defined at the beginning of the program, again to balance readability and scope.</p>
<p>With that, it allowed for the expansion of functionality within this program to not only encrypt messages, but also decrypt messages.  Following are some sample tests that include the expected output from the original issue as well as sample output from the Wikipedia example for Vigenere encryption.</p>
<pre><code>craig@Vera:~/C_Programs/Console/Vigenere/bin/Release$ ./Vigenere e bc
Message..: ABCDE ABCDE
Encrypted: BDDFF CCEEG
craig@Vera:~/C_Programs/Console/Vigenere/bin/Release$ ./Vigenere e oculorhinolaryngology
Message..: attacking tonight
Encrypted: ovnlqbpvt hznzeuz
craig@Vera:~/C_Programs/Console/Vigenere/bin/Release$ ./Vigenere d oculorhinolaryngology
Message..: ovnlqbpvt hznzeuz
Decrypted: attacking tonight
</code></pre>
<p>The main takeaway is not that the resulting code from the initial issue is incorrect, as it does work, but rather to provide some food for thought on how to review initial code to come up with iterative steps to utilize usual and customary coding methods to make evaluating the code easier and more streamline without sacrificing functionality.</p>
